ce:section.ce:para:
In this work, we have developed carbonized nanogels (CNGsQur) that display antiviral, antioxidative, and anti-inflammatory activities, which were prepared by mild pyrolysis of quercetin (Scheme 1
                     ). Quercetin is a flavonoid found in many plants, vegetables, and fruits, and it is a component in many Chinese herbal medicines [39]. In addition, quercetin has also been widely used as an antioxidant in dietary supplements and has been shown to inhibit IAVs infection in vitro 
                     [40]. However, its medical applications have been limited by its low water solubility, stability and antiviral activity. Compared with the raw material, our CNGsQur reported herein exhibit prominent antiviral potency, high antioxidative activity, and superior solubility. In vitro cytotoxicity and hemolysis analysis demonstrates that the CNGsQur exhibit good biocompatibility. Furthermore, in IAVs-induced mouse models, we show that the CNGsQur-treated mice displayed a higher survival rate and potently protective effect against morbidity.

The high-resolution transmission electron microscopy (HRTEM) images of the CNGsQur show a graphitic lattice fringes (002) plane with a d-spacing of 0.36 nm (insets in Fig. 1A), which implies that the few-layered graphene-like structures resemble a non-ideal twisted graphitic structure (e.g., turbostratic graphene) that are embedded in the nanogel matrix [50]. This partially carbonized structure of the CNGsQur was corroborated by the XRD pattern, which displays a very broad band at 2θ of 27° (inset to Fig. S1, 
                           Supplementary Information
                        ) [50]. The peak (002) is attributed to the orientation of the aromatic ring carbon reticulated layers in the three-dimensional arrangement. In addition, diffraction profiles of all purified CNGsQur exhibit some sharp peaks, which were similar to solid quercetin. These are attributed to the self-organization of pyrolytic molecules or polymers derived from quercetin on the surface of the CNGsQur. The mild carbonation leads to in situ formation of the partially carbonized structures embedded in the CNGsQur, which can stabilize the large gel-like structure (i.e., supramolecular structures) of the nanogels, though it did not possess any antiviral effect. The carbonized structure of CNGsQur was further analyzed by Raman spectroscopy. As shown in Fig. S2 (
                           Supplementary Information
                        ), only the CNGsQur prepared at higher temperatures (i.e., CNGsQur270 and CNGsQur290) possess characteristic D and G bands at ca. 1360 and 1590 cm−1, respectively. The D/G band ratio in CNGsQur270 and CNGsQur290 are similar (ca. 0.9). The G band intensity of CNGsQur270 and CNGsQur290 is greater than that of D band, indicating that embedded carbonized graphene dots are mainly composed sp2 graphitic carbons with sp3 carbon defects.

The elemental analysis (EA) of the CNGsQur showed that the mass percentage of oxygen in the CNGsQur exceeds 50% (Table S1, 
                           Supplementary Information
                        ), suggesting that during the pyrolysis, some carbon atoms were oxidized to form oxygen-containing functional groups (e.g., CO and COH). The oxygen content in the CNGsQur230 was 59.8%, which decreased to 50.8% as the synthesis temperature was increased to 290 °C, whilst the carbon content increased from 36.9% to 45.5%. This result supported that as the synthesis temperature of CNGsQur increased, the degree of carbonization likewise increased.

We then compared quercetin and the CNGsQur by using Fourier transform infrared (FT-IR) spectroscopy (Fig. S3, 
                           Supplementary Information
                        ), and found that the CNGsQur preserve many chemical groups from the precursor molecule. For instance, bands with contributions from aromatic out-of-plane (oop) CH bending and oop ring bending (940–600 cm−1), OH bending of the phenol group (1379 cm−1), CO stretching of the aryl ketonic ring (1666 cm−1), and O  H group stretching (3550–3200 cm−1) are found in both samples [57]. In addition, a strong band could be detected at 1080 cm−1 in CNGsQur that suggests the formation of ether bonds (COC), supporting that quercetin undergoes condensation polymerization during the formation of the CNGs [58]. The broad band attributed to aromatic CC stretching (1610–1510 cm−1) is mainly due to the destruction of the B-C ring structure of quercetin to form a cyclic alkene [57]. X-ray photoelectron spectroscopy (XPS) analyses further examine the functional groups derived from quercetin on the surface of CNGsQur270 (Fig. S4, 
                           Supplementary Information
                        ). XPS spectra reveal that CNGsQur270 possess chemical substructures of quercetin (CC/CC, COC/CO, and CO) with a different composition ratio. Compared to pristine quercetin, the higher proportion of COC/CO and CC/CC in CNGsQur270 further confirms the condensation polymerization and carbonization during the formation of the CNGs. However, the incomplete carbonization process results in the formation of highly crosslinked networks (supramolecular nanogels) with abundant quercetin-like moieties. These results support the formation of CNGsQur through a relatively mild carbonization process. Compared with carbonized polymer dots (CPDs) with a full-carbon core structure with short polymer chains on their surface [59], the colloidal structures of our CNGs have highly flexible polymeric quercetin-derived moieties on their surface.

We studied the virus inhibition activity and the possible mechanism of our CNGsQur against the H1N1 variant of influenza A virus by a plaque assay in three different conditions: co-treatment, pre-treatment, and post-treatment (Fig. 2
                        A; see explanations for these conditions in Experimental section of Plaque inhibition assay). Quercetin and its derivatives have been reported to inhibit viral cell fusion by interacting with the hemagglutinin subunit on the surface of the H1N1 [60]. In addition to the direct binding of viral particles, polyphenolic compounds have been found to regulate the endocytic pathway of host cells to impede cell absorption of viruses [61,62]. Therefore, as expected, quercetin (10 μg mL−1) displayed a better inhibitory effect on H1N1 virus plaque with co-treatment (ca. 70%), compared to pre-treatment and post-treatment (<35%). Similar results were also observed for CNGsQur, which strongly inhibited the formation of virus plaques under co-treatment. However, we noted CNGsQur270 exhibits better antiviral effects than quercetin and other CNGs in post-treatment assays. For our different types of CNGsQur, their half-maximum effective concentration (EC50) values by co-treatment for the H1N1 virus were in the range of 0.7–4.8 µg mL−1 (Table 1
                        ). Among them, CNGsQur270 exhibited the best antiviral activity with an EC50 of 0.7 μg mL−1, which is 5.7-fold lower than that of pristine quercetin. The EC50 value of CNGsQur270 for H1N1 is also much lower than that of clinical antiviral drugs (e.g., amantadine, ribavirin, and zanamivir; 3.7–24.0 μg mL−1) [63,64] and as reported for nanomaterials (e.g., copper iodide particles, silver nanoparticles, and zinc oxide nanoparticles; 17–125 μg mL−1) against IVAs [65–67]. By retaining more moieties related to the B-C ring of the cinnamoyl system, the surface of the CNGsQur270 is endowed with a better capacity for adsorption of the virus particle. In control experiments, graphene oxide (lateral size ∼250 nm) and other carbonized nanomaterials prepared from ammonium citrate at 180 °C (∼5 nm) and lysine hydrochloride at 270 °C (∼120 nm) exhibited negligible inhibitory effect at co-treatment concentrations of up to 50 μg mL−1 (Fig. S5, 
                           Supplementary Information
                        ), implying that specific quercetin moieties on CNGsQur play a crucial role to interact with H1N1. We further verified the possible virus adsorption mechanism with TEM. After incubating H1N1 with CNGsQur270 (10 μg mL−1) for 10 min, CNGsQur270 with their “velcro-like” feature covered the H1N1 particles, which seemingly causes the H1N1 to lose its infective activity at the initial stage (Fig. 2B).

We first evaluated the biocompatibility of CNGsQur270 with an in vitro hemolysis assay. The CNGsQur270 did not cause hemolysis to red blood cells (RBCs) in biological solutions, even at concentrations as high as 100 μg mL−1 (Fig. S6, 
                           Supplementary Information
                        ). The cytotoxicity of various concentrations of CNGsQur270 was further studied with MDCK cells. After exposure to CNGsQur270, the cell survival rate after 72 h of incubation showed no significant cytotoxic effect. In fact, the growth rate even increased slightly for MDCK cells subjected to CNGsQur270 treatment at a concentration of 100 μg mL−1 (Fig. S7, 
                           Supplementary Information
                        ). A growth effect promoted by quercetin at a certain concentration range has also been reported in previous studies [71,72]. Since CNGsQur retain many quercetin-derived functional groups on the surface of the gel structure, we speculate that they might be the reason for the similar growth promotion effect. A further increase in the test concentration of CNGsQur showed that it does not interfere with the normal growth of MDCK cells, even at extremely high concentrations (600 μg mL−1). The 50% cytotoxic concentration (CC50) of quercetin and CNGsQur was 254.7 μg mL−1 and >600 μg mL−1 (Table 1), respectively. Compared with the previously reported CC50 values of metal nanoparticles having anti-H1N1 properties (ca. 100–200 μg mL−1), CNGsQur shows lower cytotoxicity [65–67]. The selectivity index (SI; CC50/EC50) clearly shows that CNGsQur270 (> 857.1) is more effective and potentially safer for future clinical application for H1N1 virus inhibition than quercetin (63.7) and other CNGsQur (>125.0). We also noted that the SI values of clinical antiviral drugs for IVAs, such as amantadine, baicalin, deitiforin, ribavirin, and rimantadine (4–81), are much lower than that of CNGsQur270 
                        [73,74].

We further evaluated the biocompatibility of CNGsQur270 
                        in vivo to test their potency for H1N1 virus therapy. Six-week-old mice were placed in a closed chamber (4 L), and an aerosol of CNGsQur270 was sprayed (500 μg mL−1; 8 mL) into the chamber for them to inhale naturally. Also, its effects on organ function and normal physiology were evaluated after four weeks. During this period, the weight changes of the mice (n = 12) were monitored. The average body weight of the control group and the CNGsQur270-treated group were 125% and 118%, respectively, during the 30-day observation period, with no significant difference observed (p > 0.05) (Fig. S8, 
                           Supplementary Information
                        ). Detailed histological analysis of the organs, such as the lungs, liver, kidney, and spleen, also showed signs of good health (Fig. S9, 
                           Supplementary Information
                        ). More specifically, the lung tissues of the mice showed that their architecture is preserved with a spongy structure, clear alveoli, and thin inter-alveolar septa (Fig. S9a). The hepatic, renal, and spleen histology further showed well-arranged hepatocytes with a regular nuclear-cytoplasmic ratio, undamaged glomerular tufts in the renal parenchyma, and typical lymphoid follicles architecture in a spleen section (Fig. S9b-d). These results indicate that exposure of the mice to even a high concentration of CNGsQur270 did not cause any histological changes or structural damage to their organs. Other reports, however, indicate that high concentrations of nanoparticles (e.g., Ag NPs, Au NPs, TiO2 NPs, SiO2 NPs, ZnO NPs, and CuO NPs) in the air may cause lung edema, pulmonary fibrosis, and large foci of pneumonia [75–80]. In contrast, our CNGsQur270 exhibit high antiviral activity in vitro (EC50 = 0.7 µg mL−1) and good biocompatibility in vivo. Therefore, we next explored an in vivo animal model of H1N1 infection.

BALB/c mouse models were used to examine the antiviral effect of CNGsQur270 with respect to aerosol inhalation of the H1N1. Six-week-old mice were placed in a closed chamber, whereupon the aerosol of H1N1 in PBS was sprayed into the chamber for natural inhaling of virus to infect the alveolar tissue. After 6 h, the infected mouse was further treated aerosol sample from PBS (as a control), quercetin, or CNGsQur270. Mice subjected to H1N1 only were initially observed to lose weight, have ruffled fur or lethargy, and subsequently hunched and displayed tachypnea on day 5. Severe clinical symptoms appeared after 6 days of infection, such as labored breathing, greasy fur, and reduced mobility. Finally, they died on day 11 (Fig. 4
                        ). The group post-treated with pristine quercetin did not show obvious antiviral effects, whereby the weight loss rate and mortality within 11 days were almost the same as the control group, albeit with a slight delay in the onset of clinical symptoms. In sharp contrast, the majority (>80%) of mice post-treated with CNGsQur270 survived 14 days post-infection even if they experienced significant symptoms (Fig. 4A). Consistent with the high survival rate, the average clinical scores of the CNGsQur270-treated infected mice were significantly higher than those of the other infected mice (Fig. 4B and Table S2, 
                           Supplementary Information
                        ). In addition, all groups of infected mice showed dramatic weight loss, which decreased to 62.1%−68.4% after day 11 (Fig. 4C). Subsequently, only the CNGsQur270-treated group survived to day 14 with a slight increase in body weight (71.2%).

Further analysis of lung tissue on day 7 after H1N1 infection revealed that the lung histopathology of the mice shows microscopic lesions of the H1N1 infected group, characterized by thickening of the alveolar septum (black arrow) accompanied by an increase in the number of interstitial macrophages and lymphocytes (green arrows; Fig. 5
                        ). Although the lung tissue of the quercetin-treated mice showed a larger alveolar space, however, microvascular thrombosis (red arrows) and an abnormal number of immune cells (green arrows) were still observed. Compared to the other two H1N1-infected groups, CNGsQur270-treated mice had fewer abnormal changes in lung parenchyma and interstitium, which exhibited similar characteristics to mock mice. The results of these clinical symptoms were consistent with quantitative reverse transcription-polymerase chain reaction (RT-qPCR) analysis to quantify the viral titers of H1N1 (HA mRNA expression level) in lung tissue, with the CNGsQur270-treated group exhibiting a good antiviral effect, i.e., the hemagglutinin mRNA expression level was significantly lower than in the PBS- and quercetin-treated infected groups (Fig. S10, 
                           Supplementary Information
                        ). Differ from the standard procedure of in vitro post-treatment, the highly biocompatible CNGsQur270 continued to exert biological activity in lung tissue after inhalation. The H1N1-infected mice were given CNGsQur270 daily through aerosol inhalation until day 7. Therefore, we believe the inhaled CNGsQur270 with a size > 300 nm can be specific and long-term accumulated in the lung tissues. Considering the excellent virus adsorption performance of CNGsQur270 reflected in vitro co-treatment, CNGsQur270 persisted in lung tissue to strongly suppress the virus's spread. In future work, we will evaluate the long-term therapeutic effects, biodistribution, and biodegradation of CNGsQur270.

In the inflammatory response, the expression levels of a related gene, IL-17 was up-regulated after viral inhalation infection (Fig. S11, 
                           Supplementary Information
                        ). IL-10 is an anti-inflammatory cytokine and is not affected by the H1N1 virus-induced pulmonary inflammation response. Consistent with previous reports, quercetin treatment induced the expression of IL-10, which counter-regulates the production and function of proinflammatory cytokines to alleviate the inflammatory symptoms [81]. Similar results were also found in the CNGsQur270-treated group. Although quercetin has been reported to enhance the levels of antioxidative enzymes and reduce the inflammatory responses induced by H1N1 infection in mice [40], our CNGsQur270 show superior effects relative to quercetin. CNGsQur270 exhibits effectively anti-inflammatory effects along with high antiviral activities and bioavailability of CNGsQur270, thereby potentially reducing inflammatory lung pathology. Many synthetic compounds (e.g., matrix-2 protein inhibitors and neuraminidase inhibitors) have been reported to exhibit inhibitory activities against H1N1 virus [63,64]. However, these chemicals have also been found to be neurotoxic or cause serious side effects, especially in young children [82,83]. In addition to synthetic compounds, natural compounds, such as flavones, terpenes, polyphenols, and steroids, also show great potential as anti-H1N1 drugs [84–87]. The EC50 value of these natural compounds is, however, much higher (>4.0 µg mL−1) than our CNGsQur270 (0.7 µg mL−1). The SI value evaluation also revealed the advantages of CNGsQur270 (>857.1) against the H1N1 virus (Table 1). It is worth noting that most studies on natural compounds with anti-H1N1 effects have only been verified in vitro. Our rodent model showed that pure quercetin had no obvious blocking effect on H1N1 virus inhalation infection. In contrast, CNGsQur270 synthesized through a mild carbonization process could effectively attach to the virus to prevent it from entering the host cells, and also suppress inflammation caused by the virus in the body.
